Travel Package Purchase Prediction¶

Description¶

Background and Context¶

A company named "Visit with us" is updating its business model. The Policy Maker of the company wants to establish a viable business model to expand the customer base.

A viable business model is a central concept that helps to understand the existing ways of doing business and ways in which the business could be updated to benefit the tourism sector.

One of the ways to expand the customer base is to introduce new offering of packages.

Currently, there are 5 types of packages the company is offering - Basic, Standard, Deluxe, Super Deluxe, King. Looking at last year's data, it was observed that 18% of the customers purchased the packages.

However, it was difficult to identify the potential customers because customers were contacted at random without looking at the available information.

The company is now planning to launch a new product i.e. Wellness Tourism Package. Wellness Tourism is defined as Travel that allows the traveler to maintain, enhance or kick-start a healthy lifestyle, and support or increase one's sense of well-being.

This time the company wants to harness available data of existing and potential customers to target the right customers.

The purpose of this case study is to analyze existing customers' data and build a model to predict potential customers who will purchase the newly introduced travel package and provide recommendations to the Policy Maker. The model will be built to make predictions before a customer is contacted.

Objective¶

To predict which customer is more likely to purchase the newly introduced travel package.

Data Dictionary¶

Customer details:¶

  • CustomerID: Unique customer ID
  • ProdTaken: Whether the customer has purchased a package or not (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Age: Age of customer
  • TypeofContact: How customer was contacted (Company Invited or Self Inquiry)
  • CityTier: City tier depends on the development of a city, population, facilities, and living standards. The categories are ordered i.e. Tier 1 > Tier 2 > Tier 3. It's the city the customer lives in.
  • Occupation: Occupation of customer
  • Gender: Gender of customer
  • NumberOfPersonVisiting: Total number of persons planning to take the trip with the customer
  • PreferredPropertyStar: Preferred hotel property rating by customer
  • MaritalStatus: Marital status of customer
  • NumberOfTrips: Average number of trips in a year by customer
  • Passport: The customer has a passport or not (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • OwnCar: Whether the customers own a car or not (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • NumberOfChildrenVisiting: Total number of children with age less than 5 planning to take the trip with the customer
  • Designation: Designation of the customer in the current organization
  • MonthlyIncome: Gross monthly income of the customer

Customer interaction data:¶

  • PitchSatisfactionScore: Sales pitch satisfaction score
  • ProductPitched: Product pitched by the salesperson
  • NumberOfFollowups: Total number of follow-ups has been done by the salesperson after the sales pitch
  • DurationOfPitch: Duration of the pitch by a salesperson to the customer

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

Combine single and Unmarried into one category¶

In [20]:
#According to the Candian government website the marital status 'Single (including living common law)' is defined as
#"persons who have never married (including all persons less than 15 years of age). It also includes persons whose
# marriage has been legally annulled who were single before the annulled marriage and who have not remarried. 
#Those who live with a common-law partner are included in this category.'

#Going with the above definition we will combine Single and Unmarried. However, in the real world we would have to 
#consult with the business to ensure that this assumption is correct. 

#Change the Unmaried value to Single so they are combined into one category.
data['MaritalStatus'].replace('Unmarried',  'Single', inplace=True)

# functions to treat outliers by flooring and capping
def treat_outliers(df, col):
    """
    Treats outliers in a variable

    df: dataframe
    col: dataframe column
    """
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # all the values smaller than Lower_Whisker will be assigned the value of Lower_Whisker
    # all the values greater than Upper_Whisker will be assigned the value of Upper_Whisker
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker)

    return df
def treat_outliers_all(df, col_list):
    """
    Treat outliers in a list of variables

    df: dataframe
    col_list: list of dataframe columns
    """
    for c in col_list:
        df = treat_outliers(df, c)

    return df

Model evaluation criterion¶

The model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predicting a customer will not buy a product and the customer does buy a product.
  2. Predicting a customer will buy a product, and the customer doesn't buy a product.

Which case is more important?¶

Predicting a customer will not buy a product, and the customer does buy a product.

Which metric to optimize?¶

We would want Recall to be maximized, the greater the Recall higher the chances of minimizing false negatives.

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [52]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

#!pip install lightgbm
import lightgbm as lgb

#LightGBM can use categorical features as input directly. It doesn’t need to convert to one-hot encoding, 
#and is much faster than one-hot encoding (about 8x speed-up).
#Also we will not be imputing the null values as LightGBM takes care of the null values

#Loading train and test data again without one-hot encoding 
XL = data.drop(["ProdTaken"], axis=1)
YL = data["ProdTaken"]

# Splitting data in train and test sets
XL_train, XL_test, yl_train, yl_test = train_test_split(
    XL, YL, test_size=0.30, random_state=1, stratify=YL
)
lgb_model = lgb.LGBMClassifier(learning_rate=0.09,max_depth=-5,random_state=42)
lgb_model.fit(XL_train,yl_train,eval_set=[(XL_test,yl_test),(XL_train,yl_train)],
          verbose=20,eval_metric='logloss')

Permutation Feature Importance¶

https://machinelearningmastery.com/calculate-feature-importance-with-python/

We can look at feature importance using Permutation. Permutation feature importance is a technique for calculating relative importance scores that is independent of the model used.We can use the Stacking_Classifier model and try to get feature importance.

In [102]:
#Update the value for the columns that have nulls to the median of train. 
#This will be updated for the X data frame
X.loc[data['DurationOfPitch'].isnull(), 'DurationOfPitch'] = X_train['DurationOfPitch'].median()
X.loc[data['MonthlyIncome'].isnull(), 'MonthlyIncome'] = X_train['MonthlyIncome'].median()
X.loc[data['Age'].isnull(), 'Age'] = X_train['Age'].median()
X.loc[data['NumberOfTrips'].isnull(), 'NumberOfTrips'] = X_train['NumberOfTrips'].median()

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
from sklearn.inspection import permutation_importance
results = permutation_importance(stacking_classifier, X, Y, scoring='recall')
p_importance = results.importances_mean
indices = np.argsort(p_importance)
plt.figure(figsize=(12,12))
plt.title('Feature Importances')
plt.barh(range(len(indices)), p_importance[indices], color='violet', align='center')
plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), [feature_names[i] for i in indices])
plt.xlabel('Relative Importance')
plt.show()

Using Permutation Feature Importance and Stacking_classifier as the model we get the following feature importance. Passport, Designation_Executive, DurationOfPitch, MaritalStatus_Single, Age, and CityTier3, and it also included PreferredPropertyStar_5. The features are mostly consistent with one ones we saw with other models.

Model Conclusions¶

Overall the models improved after hyperparameter tuning. The best model for this case study is the Stacking Classifier as it gives the best Recall score of 0.903. The model to give the best Precision score is Bagging Estimator Tuned with 0.935. If we take both Precision and Recall into consideration, then the best model will be XGBoost Classifier with the highest f1 score. But for this case study Recall is more important.

The models used by Stacking Classifier were, rf_tuned, gbc_tuned, dtree_estimator and the final estimator was xgb_tuned. Looking at the first few feautre importances for these models, we can see that all the four models indicate Passport, Designation_Executive, and MaritalStatus_Single as Important Features. The models for Random Forest Tuned, GBC Tuned and DecisionTree Estimator also included Age and DurationOfPitch as important features. Decision Tree and XGB_tuned models also included CityTier 3 and XGB-Tuned included ProdctPitched_Basic and Occupation_LargeBusiness as important features.

Using Permutation Feature Importance and Stacking_classifier as the model we get the similar feature importance. The Permutation Feature Importance also included PreferredPropertyStar_5. The feautre importances were mostly consistent with one ones we saw with other models.

Recommendations¶

The Business, "Visit with us", should give importance to customers who have a Passport. The models indicated that Passport is an important feature for predicting the customers who will buy a product. Also the bivariate analysis showed that customers who had a Passport bought a product as compared to customer who did not have a Passport.

The business should also look at customers who are Executives. the model showed that customers who had a Designation of Exceutive bought a product.

The business should look at the DurationOfPitch. The higher the duration the more likely that the customer will buy a product.

The customer should consider Age and MonthlyIncome of the customers. Also the bivariate anaysis showed a correlation between Age and MonthlyIncome.

The business should look at customers who live in CityTier3. The models showed that City Tier 3 is an important feature.

The business should consider the marital status of the customers. The models indicated that Single customers as an important feature.

The business can also look at Occupation. The model showed that Customers who work at Large businesses are more likely to buy a product.

The model also found that customers who were pitched with the Basic product were more likely to buy a product.

The business should also look at the PreferredPropertyStar for their customers. Customers who had PreferredPropertyStar as 5 were more likely to buy a product.
